Cover.Slides and datasets to accompany coronav: Hospital Admissions (UK)
Source: NHS England, Welsh Government, Scottish Government, Northern Ireland Executive.
Data are for: NHS trusts and IS providers.

England data captures people admitted to hospital who already had a confirmed COVID-19 status at point of admission, and adds those who tested positive in the previous 24 hours whilst in hospital. Inpatients diagnosed with COVID-19 after admission are assumed to have been admitted on the day prior to their diagnosis.

Wales data includes confirmed and suspected cases, and is the number of admissions to the hospital in the previous 24 hour period up to 9am. The status of COVID/non-COVID is as at the time of reporting not at time of admission.
Northern Ireland data includes suspected and confirmed COVID-19 admissions by admission date.

Data for Scotland provides the profile of admissions into hospital for patients who tested positive for COVID-19 in the 14 days prior to admission to hospital, on the day of their admission or during their stay in hospital. The data are published weekly by Public Health Scotland: https://beta.isdscotland.org/find-publications-and-data/population-health/covid-19/covid-19-statistical-report/
Ventilator beds with COVID-19 patients (UK)
Source: NHS England, Welsh Government, Scottish Government, Northern Ireland Executive.
Overall number of Mechanical Ventilation beds that are occupied by COVID patients, by nation.
This measure includes both Nightingale hospitals and Dragon's Heart/Ysbyty Calon y Ddraig field hospital.
For a ventilator bed to be "available" this requires more than just the physical bed and ventilator.
Wales mechanical ventilator beds cover invasive ventilated beds in a critical care setting, plus those outside of a critical care environment.
Scottish figures include people in ICU with confirmed or suspected COVID-19, and may include a small number of patients who are not on mechanical ventilation.
England figures include the number of COVID-19 patients in beds which are capable of delivering mechanical ventilation.
Northern Ireland figures include the number of COVID-19 patients in beds which are capable of delivering mechanical ventilation.
Daily COVID-19 deaths confirmed with a positive test (UK)
Source: Department of Health and Social Care, sourced from NHS England, Public Health England and the devolved administrations.
These data can be downloaded here:
https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/downloads/csv/coronavirus-deaths_latest.csv
7-day rolling average (mean) of daily deaths.
7-day rolling sum of daily deaths is the total of daily deaths for the current day and the six previous days.
UK deaths are reported when paperwork is filed, rather than time of death. Deaths are reported in the 24 hours up to 5pm on the previous day.
New Cases (UK)
Source: Department of Health and Social Care, Welsh Government, Scottish Government, Northern Ireland Executive.
Cases are reported when lab tests are completed. This may be a few days after initial testing.
Testing capacity is increasing, which is resulting in a greater number of observed cases. There are likely many more cases than currently recorded here.
There may be a small percentage of cases where the same person has had more than one positive test result for COVID-19 in Pillar 2.
DHSC have published explanatory notes to accompany this data:
https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public
Infection survey (England)
Source: Office for National Statistics, COVID-19 Infection Survey.

These statistics refer to infections reported in the community, by which we mean private households. These figures exclude infections reported in hospitals, care homes or other institutional settings.
Please see the statistical bulletin for more methodological information on the COVID-19 Infection Survey:
https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/healthandsocialcare/conditionsanddiseases/bulletins/coronaviruscovid19infectionsurveypilot/5june2020
Weekly deaths registrations (England and Wales)
Source: Office for National Statistics.
Figures include deaths of non-residents.
Based on date of death that was registered rather than occurred.
All figures for 2020 are provisional.
The ICD-10 definitions are as follows: COVID-19 (U07.1 and U07.2)
The number of death registrations was impacted by the Early May Bank Holiday; the number of registrations decreased from 2,950 deaths on Friday 1 May 2020 to 88 deaths on Friday 8 May 2020.
https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/bulletins/deathsregisteredweeklyinenglandandwalesprovisional/weekending29may2020
